[4] Balochistan: fatal case count
Date: Tue 23 Aug 2016
Source: Pak Observer [edited]
http://pakobserver.net/9-killed-by-congo-virus-in-quetta/


At least 9 people have died so far from Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) in Quetta. According to details, 84 patients have been brought to Fatima Jinnah General and Chest Hospital in the [current] year [2016]. At least 22 of them have been confirmed with the disease, and 3 are still under treatment.

One of the affected patients is said to be in better condition while the blood test samples of 2 others have been sent to Karachi. They include a 30-year-old from Qila Saifullah and a 35-year-old from Quetta.

Fatima Jinnah General and Chest Hospital is the only centre in Balochistan to treat Congo virus where a large number of patients arrive not only from the far flung areas of the province but also from neighboring country Afghanistan.

Despite consecutive cases of Congo virus, no laboratory is present in the hospital for its identification. The hospital administration has warned that 8 districts of the province are vulnerable to the disease.

Abbottabad (Khyber Pukhtoonkhwa)
--------------------------------
The Department of Livestock and Dairy Development Khyber Pakhtunkhwa has executed fumigation around the cattle markets in all districts of Hazara division for controlling the possible outbreak of Congo.

Director Livestock Dr Abdul Waheed Alvi said [Mon 22 Aug 2016], that the all the sacrificial animals that have been brought to cattle markets in Battagram, Mansehra, Abbottabad, and Haripur have been vaccinated against ticks.

He said all the owners of cattle markets have been directed to take precautionary measures against Congo virus to save the citizens from contracting any potential disease. He further said that after reports of 17 deaths in Balochistan, Sindh, and Punjab due to Congo virus, the department has taken emergency step to fumigate all the cattle market as well as the cattle.

Dr Waheed said that the fumigation would continue till Eid ul Azha and cattle owners have been advised to cooperate with the department in this regard.

